description.text:
See hivemonkey.com for the full project writeup, including electronics, code, Stryfe modifications, etc.

This is a case specifically designed to fit on the left side of a Nerf Stryfe and mount a particular homebrew electronics package, consisting of a Raspberry Pi Zero fitted with a Pimoroni Rainbow Hat and an ultrasonic rangefinder. The LEDs, alphanumeric display, and capacitive buttons are all available from the back of the case while the rangefinder looks forward to, well, find range. A slot on the right side of the case admits wires, since power, magazine sensing switch, and trigger switch are all located inside the body of the Stryfe.

The Rainbow Hat displays shots remaining in the magazine using the colored LEDs across the top, and displays range to target (in cm) in on the alphanumeric display. It also buzzes to let you know when the mag is either empty, or removed. The buttons on the bottom of the Hat adjust possible magazine sizes.

The mounting bracket on the case itself fits into the side cavity using the Hulker side-rail mount - secure it there with glue or whatever. The ultrasonic sensor fits nicely into the ports on the front of the lid; the support studs within the case match the mounting holes on the Hat and the top two holes on the Pi. The little extension on the far left side of the case leaves room the the Pi's microSD card to slot in without damage.

The v1 model of the lid has mounting studs inside which aren't necessary for the ultrasonic sensor, but might be useful for something else. The v2 model of the lid loses the mounting studs, and adds the rest of the Hulker siderail for cosmetic reasons and to allow a screw connection between the siderails.

The lid mates nicely to the case, but doesn't really lock in place enough that I was comfortable swinging it around with electronics inside, so I welded the lid to the case with a 3D printing pen. You could use glue or whatever. There's no way to get to the Pi's USB port to get on the network, so either be comfortable with your code or use a Pi Zero W. :)

Several different Thingiverse projects gave small bits of themselves to this Thing. Also pictured, though not included since I didn't remix it, is this great foregrip with space for a mini flashlight.

Hope you enjoy. And if you make this, and can write better code than I can - which you almost certainly can, because I'm terrible at code - please let me know, I'm pretty sure I'm doing some things the Hardest Way Possible.

title: Shoei RF-1200 Helmet GoPro FPV Chin Mount (Sturdy, Permanent)

description.text:
My brother was in a minor accident caused by a stupid driver that sped off, so i made a mount for where he wanted his new GoPro. I am sharing it here because i want others to be able to catch bad drivers.

This was designed more specifically for the size of the GoPro Session. The Session is fatter front to back, so it needed to stick out more to account for the clearance needed to tilt. If it doesn't have that tilt when in the riding position then it is mostly looking at the ground. This can easily be modified to fit other cameras or mount types too, the contour curve is the most important fitted part. When i made this i could not remove the center corner area of the curved fitting which is a bit visible. I knew that it'd be a non-issue with how close it was to the helmet and the epoxy fills it out.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

i3 MK2S

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

50-100%

Notes:

I used 50% honeycomb infill with Rigid Ink's ASA material (seriously consider picking it up for outdoor use). Supports may or may not be needed for the GoPro mount. I decided to print with them.

Mounting this in the intended style is permanent. Please do not drill holes or use screws. Doing so will created a weakness in the helmet!

Glue a GoPro screw nut into the recessed area of the mount where it will be seated (i salvaged one from another mount i have). Here is the glue i used, this stuff is incredible. ONLY use this for the nut! A couple of drops will do. Play around with it beforehand, little dots dry fast and hold super strong.

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00WHEM0UA/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Roughen the helmet and mount areas that will be glued. I used light grit sandpaper, it doesn't need much sanding. This will improve adhesion. The epoxy i used is the best that i could find after multiple hours of searching. Trust me when i say this, it works very very well. I used about 3/4th of 1oz. It needs that much to ensure that the surface areas between are entirely coated. Almost like applying thermal paste on a CPU, do the general center and let it spread. Squish it on tight, leave no gaps. Use q-tips to remove any edge oozing if there is any. Here is a link to the epoxy, you will only need 1oz:

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0039V0L2Y/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Let it sit for at least 24 hours. I hung it on a horizontal clothes pole with the helmet facing up.

It has taken minor knocks so far, about 1 month of use and no issues.

description.text:
At the request of mrhappydude I put together a PSU fan mount for the MK2S. This initial version isn't for a 120mm fan as he requested, its for a 80mm fan instead (I didn't have any 120mm fans handy).

Option 1:

I had another idea stuck in my head for this part which I also just completed and tested...
its a minimal version which prints fairly quick and lets you use any 80mm fan shroud/screen you want, but its a little tougher print... at a minimum its just 4 pegs that lock into the case that have threaded shafts and thumbscrews to hold the fan in place.

You need to print:
4x - Fan Shroud Grill Peg-thumbnut.stl
1x - Fan Shroud for Pegs.stl (only if you want to use the bundled shroud, else use can omit)

Comments greatly appreciated, let me know what you think!

Notes:

All tested parts printed in ColorFabb NGen (as I have lots) I'd normally print this in PETG, but PLA should be fine as well. 100% infill vs 20% only changes the filament use by 10cm or so, you could try it at 20%, but the few mm of savings isn't really worth it.

Build & Assembly Notes:

General:

  • I'd align the clips so the teeth are printed on the X-axis (long side front to back) or the pegs so they line up left to right to maximize the resolution as the X-Axis has the least momentum, but either orientation works (I printed both to test).

Assembly:
Option 1:

  • press the 4 printed clips into the shroud, they should ratchet into place, only push them about half way in. Look at the teeth and orient the top and bottom as required.
  • Push the fan into the shroud, it'll lock on the pins
  • Place the assembly on the side of the power supply and rock/move it side to side, top to bottom until the 4 clips pop through the PSU and lock in place, take your time, it doesn't take pressure, just movement.
  • keep rocking/pressing the assembly towards the PSU until it ratchets as far as it can and is tight.
  • if you're concerned about it coming loose.... yep... the hole in the end of the clips is just the right size for a little piece of filament to go in... put that in and they can't pop back out...

Option 2:

  • figure out which slots line up with the fan holes you need.

description.text:
This is a remix of https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1868554
A friend wanted me to print a Castle Grayskull for her boyfriends birthday present. I liked the original but wanted to make it more like the castle instead of a dice tower.
So, I cut the tower in half down the middle, mirrored it, joined it so I would have the turret without the 'face' on it. I then copied it four times and layered them around the main turret, I reduced the size of the main turret a little so it stands out more.
After I did that, I removed the overlapping circles inside the castle. After I printed it, I decided I wanted it to have a 'lid' so I made that from scratch too.
The lid (or STL called 'inner'), in Simplify 3D I reduced it to a scale of 99% because it would be too snug to put in full scale.

On 6/25/2012, I had a "Capture Your Town" session at the Field Museum in Chicago. I was joined by Matt Griffin (MBI community manager), Michael Curry (Skimbal), and Tom Burtonwood (Chicago based artist).
This thing is a scan of "Sue: The Model T. Rex". I used 123D catch for the scanning process, and Netfabb + Meshmixer for model cleanup. From the display:
"This model of Sue's head was created by Canadian Sculptor Brian Cooley. It appears in the June 1999 issue of National Geographic.
Even though it's only one-third size, all of the proportions of the model are identical to Sue's real Skull.
That's because Brian took detailed measurements before he began sculpting. Based on these measurements, he first made a scale model of the skull. Then he added muscles and other soft tissues, eyes, and finally some pebbly skin.
Life reconstructions like this model combine science and art. They are the result of close observation, scientific theory, and creative speculation."

I have included all project files: pictures, 123D files, and various revisions of a "cleaned model".
I printed mine at .27mm, 150mm/s accelerated, 4% infill, 1 shell with Jetty's "altshell.py"
Print your model at a large scale to see the ammount of detail on the skin!
This print has some overhangs on the teeth. However my results were good on my super tuned TOM. I'll improve the teeth if anybody is having trouble with printing.

Notes:

Make sure your bed is level. PRINT MULTIPLE COPIES. You will need at least 5. Use scale 1. They should be 4 layers high at 0.3mm layer height. If you scale them down, they will be too flimsy, and bend too easily. If you scale them up, they might not bend easily enough to snap together when finished.

First, cut the pieces to length. You will need 6 pieces with 3 little loops/rings each, 10 pieces with 5 loops, 14 pieces with 7 loops, and 18 pieces with 9 loops. You'll have to throw away some trimmings.

To assemble the pieces, you'll need to either grip the strands and pull the loops into each other, or push the loops together with extra-slim hobby pliers: the smaller the better. I recommend starting at the top of the structure and working your way down down. Start with 3 pieces that each have 3 loops, then add the 5 pieces with 5 loops, and so on. After you cross the halfway point, keep working your way down. DON'T make two pyramids and then try to then attach them to each other. The geometry won't allow that.

I guess this requires a bit of explanation. This is a wedge to prop open what is simply called a window in Germany, but is apparently not that common anywhere else. German windows are of a type sometimes called tilt and turn (or tilt and swing) window. (Or German window.) They open in two ways, all the way, like a door, swinging inward, or turning around the bottom edge by something like 10°, inward again, and are held in place there by a linkage. This is a wedge to prop open the window tilted inward. Push it between the moving and stationary vertical window frames.

description.text:
For use with Prusa i3 Rework X-Carriage.
The inspiration came from ch1t0's i3 extruder design. I initially began designing this extruder to work with the E3D Hotend because of the sloppy fit on the original version but the one thing I really wanted, was to install 60mm cooling fans. In addition I design a E3D 40mm shroud that works with v4, v5., plus a Dual 50mm Cooling fan holder and a 60mm Cooling Fan Holder. 2 different clamps, one is just plain and other one has extension for addons you want to put on. Fan Cover used: i3 40mm Fan Cover and Open Hardware 60mm Fan Cover. Other parts I used - RichRap's Guidler with Lever and schlem's Skulltruder Gears. Funny note: When I started the 60mm fans (I know, OVERKILL) it sounded like a jet engine and for a split second I thought my printer was going to start hovering above my desk. :) Update: Feb 8, 2015
Added v6 version for 3mm filament and also a v6 40mm Fan Shroud.

It's pretty straight forward but if you need instructions.
Go here: http://reprap.org/wiki/Prusa_i3_Rework_Extruder_assembly Note: If you decide to use the modified version, you'll need to re-adjust the position of your Y-Axis endstop. Z-Axis endstop will also need to be adjusted on both versions.

description.text:
I wanted to mount the Processing Unit (PU) on the wall near the ceiling, so I could run the headset cables across the ceiling and down. I started by mounting the PU to the wall with 3M Command Strips, but I knew I would want to take the VR rig with me at times, so I designed and printed this holder to make that easy.

It is intended for the PU unit to sit vertically, so you can mount it via either side or from the bottom, sitting on something. I used 3M Command Strips to eliminate the possibility of damage to surfaces.

Design has opening in the rear for airflow from the PU's built-in fan, as well as a slot in the front to keep the light and Sony logo visible.

UPDATE Nov 12 '17 - Uploaded a model with holes for screw mounting on both sides and the bottom. 3M Command strips weren't up to the task...

remixed_from.title: PrintrBot Simple X-axis GT2 Belt & Extension

description.text:
Increase your X travel to GT2 belt drive and 165mm print area while keeping the stock print plate. Larger area is capable with a custom plate. Requirements:
  • Well calibrated printer.
  • Ability to print 98 mm x 98 mm (use "Orientated" files), or print 125 mm length (use standard files). I installed my Y-Axis No-Sag upgrade first, then printed parts for this one (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:242185).
  • 8mm linear rods 87 mm longer than the hole center distance on your print bed. For the stock bed, that would be 254 mm long rods, which gives you 165 mm print area.
    • 2014-03-10: Updated Rod ends to increase thickness next to bed mounting bolts. 2014-03-19, RevB: Updated Rod Ends to increase thickness next to belt slot. Updated RodEnd-Mirror to move belt anchor away from Simple 2014 fan. The stock fan should clear nicely now. 2014-05-13: Added a couple files to allow for any length rod to be used. By installing "RodEnd-Mirror-Mid.stl" at the edge of your bed, and "RodEnd-Mirror-Overhang.stl" at the end of your rods, the rods can extend well past the edge of the print platform. Pass the belt thru the Mid part and anchor on the Overhang portion. This way the belt tension will pull on the ends of the rods and not bind the bed leveling screws. Design inspired by ahaer http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:215294

Assembly Tips:
  • Thread belt around timing pulley and between bearings BEFORE mounting motor plate on machine.
  • To get the belt length, secure one end of the belt in a rod end part. Temporarily snap the rod ends onto the 8mm rods and thread your belt thru the other end, and the belt tensioner. Mark where the belt comes thru the back of the belt tensioner and cut it about 15mm longer than that mark. Remove one of the belt ends to give you some working room. Fold the belt at your mark, wrap around a 6mm piece of filament, and insert into the belt tensioner. Re-install and tie-wrap both rod ends in place. Tension belt.

title: ORIGINAL Fisher Price Record Player Replacement Turntable

description.text:
We got a classic fisher price record player for our son from ebay, he loves anything mechanical and music boxes. Since it was about 50 years old, the gears were rusty and it had to be taken apart and cleaned. When I was re-assembling it, the old turntable shattered into a bunch of little pieces when I put the screw in, and I didn't even put much force on it. Instead of trying to glue the 20-30 pieces together and hope it holds, I designed a new turntable and it survived months of heavy daily use without any problems

NOTE: This is for the ORIGINAL player, not the newer electronic model
